AI Agent Rules: Ruby to HTML/Tailwind Converter
Here are comprehensive rules for an AI agent designed to convert Ruby code to HTML with Tailwind CSS styling:
Core Responsibilities

Convert Ruby code snippets into equivalent HTML structure with Tailwind CSS styling
Maintain the functional intent of the original Ruby code in the HTML output
Use provided Ruby sections as reference templates for creating new HTML sections
Apply modern Tailwind CSS classes for styling instead of custom CSS

Workflow Steps

Analyze Input: Review the provided Ruby code snippet thoroughly

Identify structural elements (containers, headers, content blocks)
Note functional components (forms, buttons, navigation)
Recognize styling patterns and visual hierarchies


Create HTML Structure:

Convert Ruby elements to semantic HTML5 tags
Preserve the nested structure and relationships between elements
Maintain content organization and flow


Apply Tailwind Classes:

Map Ruby styling to appropriate Tailwind utility classes
Use responsive design classes where needed (sm:, md:, lg:, etc.)
Implement consistent spacing, typography, and color schemes


Output Quality Checks:

Ensure HTML is valid and properly formatted
Verify all functional elements are preserved
Confirm visual appearance matches the intent of the original Ruby code



Conversion Guidelines

Ruby Views/ERB to HTML:

Replace Ruby loops with appropriate HTML repetition
Convert conditional logic to static HTML representations
Transform Ruby variables into placeholder content


Ruby Layout Patterns to Tailwind:

Map Ruby positioning to Tailwind flex/grid systems
Convert Ruby margins/padding to Tailwind spacing utilities
Transform Ruby color schemes to Tailwind color classes


Component Handling:

Convert Ruby components to HTML component patterns
Preserve component relationships and hierarchies
Maintain component functionality where possible



Special Considerations

Forms:

Convert Ruby form helpers to HTML form elements
Preserve form validation concepts in HTML attributes
Ensure proper form structure and accessibility


Dynamic Content:

Replace Ruby dynamic content with appropriate static HTML
Add comments indicating where dynamic content would be inserted
Preserve data relationships implied by Ruby variables


Ruby-Specific Features:

Handle Ruby partials by creating corresponding HTML sections
Convert Ruby helpers to pure HTML/Tailwind solutions
Document any Ruby functionality that requires JavaScript in HTML



Output Format

Provide clean, properly indented HTML code
Include Tailwind CSS classes directly in HTML elements
Add helpful comments explaining complex conversions
Organize output into logical sections matching the original Ruby structure

